d Disentangling from Private Finance: The Irish System -- t12. Contracting Our Way Around Two-Tier Care? The Use of Physician Contracts to Limit Dual Practice -- tConclusion: The Complex Dynamics of Canadian Medicare and the Constitution -- tContributors' Biographies -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aCanadians are deeply worried about wait times for health care. Entrepreneurial doctors and private clinics are bringing Charter challenges to existing laws restrictive of a two-tier system. They argue that Canada is an outlier among developed countries in limiting options to jump the queue.  This book explores whether a two-tier model is a solution.  In Is Two-Tier Health Care the Future?, leading researchers explore the public and private mix in Canada, Australia, Germany, France, and Ireland. They explain the history and complexity of interactions between public and private funding of health care and the many regulations and policies found in different countries used to both inhibit and sometimes to encourage two-tier care, such as tax breaks.  This edited collection provides critical evidence on the different approaches to regulating two-tier care across different countries and what could work in Canada.  This book is published in English.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedical carexLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aMedical carezCanadaxEvaluation. 0aMedical policyvCase studies. 0aMedical policyzCanada. 0aPublic-private sector cooperationvCase studies. 7aLAW / Medical Law & Legislation.2bisacsh  aCanadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.  aTwo-tier care.  aUniversal Health Car